  <header class="post-header">
    <div class="kicker">
      <time class="updated" datetime="2007-01-02T06:17:00+00:00">Tuesday, January 2, 2007</time>
    </div>
    <h1 class="title" >
      <a href="https://orangette.net/2007/01/happy-new/">Happy, new</a>
    </h1>
  </header>
  <div class="post-content" itemprop="articleBody">
    <p>Friends, you have been very, very good to me.  For the past couple of years, you‚Äôve been stopping by to see me on a regular basis, and you‚Äôve said some pretty nice things about the contents of my kitchen and my dinner plate.  Last spring, when <a href="http://orangette.blogspot.com/2006/04/man-plan-food-blog.html">Brandon asked me</a> to marry him, you gave a whoop and a cheer that kept me giddy for at least a week, easy.  And when, a few months ago, I started posting a little less frequently, you didn‚Äôt let slip the slightest complaint: you just kept on coming, and cheering, and saying nice things.  I owe you one ‚Äì that‚Äôs for sure.  It‚Äôs been busy back here, behind the scenes ‚Äì or the computer screen, as it were.  But it‚Äôs been the best kind of busyness imaginable, the sort of busyness that brings lots of Champagne and jumping up and down, the sort of busyness that comes with getting <strong>a book deal</strong>.  <a href="http://orangette.blogspot.com/2006/12/meantime.html">I promised</a> you some big news for the New Year, and I mean to deliver.</p>
<p>When I started this site, I wanted just two things: a place to write about food, and a few readers to keep me accountable.  I hardly even knew what a blog <em>was</em>, people.  A friend had to explain it to me, for Pete‚Äôs sake.  But somewhere along the line, after a year or so, I found that I sort of liked this blogging thing, and you know, I thought, it might be nice, maybe, to sit around and write <em>all the time</em>.  So an idea was hatched, and ‚Äì to make a long story short &#8211; many months, one book proposal, one agent, one editor, a lot of ‚Äú<em>Holy crap</em>!‚Äùs, and one contract later, here I am.  [It wasn‚Äôt quite that easy, of course, but as some say of childbirth, so I say of book proposals: you forget the pain as soon as it‚Äôs over.]  I couldn‚Äôt be happier to announce today that I am writing <strong>a cookbook</strong>, a narrative cookbook crammed full of new, original recipes and stories.  The manuscript is due on December 15, 2007, and will be published by Simon &amp; Schuster.  And as of the end of this month, I will be ‚Äì [<em>small, thrilling gasp of terror</em>] ‚Äì leaving my job to write it.  As it turns out, 2007 will not only be the year that Brandon and I are married, but also be the year that I become a full-time writer.  I know I‚Äôve said it before, and about other things, but <em>hooo boy</em>.  I mean it.</p>
<p>This announcement would be sorely lacking without an enormous, sung-from-the-rooftops ‚ÄúThank you!‚Äù to a dear friend known to many as the <a href="http://glutenfreegirl.blogspot.com/">Gluten-Free Girl</a>.  Shauna, girlfriend, good lord, I‚Äôm so happy to have you in my life.  Thank you for everything, and for you.</p>
<p>I also owe a big one to Brandon, the best first reader a writer could ever want.  He inspires me, pushes me, and keeps me true, and one night during the long slog of the book proposal, when I burst into big, loud, sloppy tears at the dinner table, he gave me a firm back rub and took me out for a fancy dessert.  He knows just what to do.</p>
<p>My lucky stars have been very good to me this year, and so have you, friends.  I wouldn‚Äôt be writing this post right now ‚Äì much less an entire book ‚Äì if you weren‚Äôt here to read it.  Thank you, thank you, <em>thank you</em> for that.  I‚Äôm so happy to share it all with you.</p>
<p><a href="http://photos1.blogger.com/x/blogger/5046/497/1600/96509/271018641_859519b78d.jpg"><img decoding="async" alt="" src="http://orangette.net/wp-content/uploads/2007/01/271018641_859519b78d.jpg" border="0" /></a><br />Happy New Year, everyone.</p>
  </div>
